Now in theory, someone could hand craft a html page to fool the grails binding mechanism to update a bunch of objects in the model that they have no right to be updating.

Now I know that grails allows you to specify which fields are bound. But I&#39;ve got really complex and deeply nested model. If I started having to specify everywhere which fields could be bound, it would be a mess. Furthermore, it would destroy the application, because I WANT those objects to be bound into the model, I just don&#39;t the user to be updating them. Furthermore, some of them are collections, and trying to know what can or can&#39;t be bound in a collection of arbitrary size... I can&#39;t see that working practically

But what I could do, at least in theory, is in the controller methods that do updates, is specify to hibernate, ok these are the objects that I want you to update, nothing else that might happen to be in the session.

For example, here&#39;s a grails controller method for updating the user&#39;s password:

&lt;pre&gt;
   

     def personalUpdatePassword(AuthCommand m) {
